definition.value: A dihydroxyanthraquinone that is 1,4-dihydroxy-9,10-anthraquinone which is substituted by 6-hydroxy-1,4-diazahexyl groups at positions 5 and 8.
A product in capsule, tablet or liquid form that provide essential nutrients, such as a vitamin, an essential mineral, a protein, an herb, or similar nutritional substance.
A dicarboxylic acid monoamide resulting from the formal condensation of one of the carboxy groups of terephthalic acid with ammonia.

A substance that possess antiestrogenic actions but can also produce estrogenic effects as well. It acts as complete or partial agonist or as antagonist. It can be either steroidal or nonsteroidal in structure.
The zwitterion formed from taurine by transfer of a proton from the sulfonyl to the amino group.  It is the major species existing at physiological pH.
A hydrochloride salt resulting from the reaction of equimolar amounts of raloxifene and hydrogen chloride.
Any retinoic acid receptor (RAR) agonist with specificity for RARalpha and RARbeta.

A steroid ester resulting from the formal condensation of the carboxy group of acetic acid with the 17-hydroxy group of cyproterone. It is an antiandrogenic drug which has recently been recognized to promote the occurrence and growth of intracranial meningiomas.
A salt of citric acid.
A compound that interacts with progesterone receptors in target tissues to bring about effects similar to those of progesterone.
Any organic heterobicyclic compound consisting of a benzene ring fused to a thiopyran.
A drug used to treat psoriasis.

A seco-cholestane that is 26,27-cyclo-9,10-secocholesta-5,7,10,22-tetraene carrying additional hydroxy substituents at positions 1, 3 and 24. It is used (as its hydrate) in combination with betamethasone dipropionate, a corticosteroid, for the topical treatment of plaque psoriasis in adult patients.
Flavone hydroxylated at positions 3', 4', 5, 5' and 7.

A topoisomerase inhibitor that inhibits DNA topoisomerase (ATP-hydrolysing), EC 5.99.1.3 (also known as topoisomerase II and as DNA gyrase), which catalyses ATP-dependent breakage of both strands of DNA, passage of the unbroken strands through the breaks, and rejoining of the broken strands.
A drug which acts to reduce estrogenic activity in the body, either by reducing the amount of estrogen or by reducing the activity of whatever estrogen is present.
Any 1-benzopyran with an aryl substituent at position 3. The term was originally restricted to natural products, but is now also used to describe semi-synthetic and fully synthetic compounds.
A member of the class of  acridines that is 9,10-dihydroacridine substituted by an oxo group at position 9.
An N-hydroxy-alpha-amino acid bearing a 5-thiahexyl substituent at the 2-position.
Any N-acyl amino acid which has formyl as the acyl group.
Any amino acid in which at least one hydrogen attached to the amino group is replaced by a hydroxy group.
An N-hydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 6-thiaheptyl substituent at the 2-position.
An N-hydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 7-thiaoctyl substituent at the 2-position.
An N-hydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 8-thianonyl substituent at the 2-position.
An N-hydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 9-thiadecyl substituent at the 2-position.
An N,N-dihydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 9-thiadecyl substituent at the 2-position.
An N-hydroxy amino acid in which the nitrogen of the parent amino acid is substituted by two hydroxy groups.
An N,N-dihydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 5-thiahexyl substituent at the 2-position.
An N,N-dihydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 6-thiaheptyl substituent at the 2-position.
An N,N-dihydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 7-thiaoctyl substituent at the 2-position.
An N,N-dihydroxy-alpha-amino acid having a 8-thianonyl substituent at the 2-position.
A polyprenylbenzoquinone that is fumigatin which is substituted by an all-trans-decaprenyl group at position 6.
A polyprenylbenzoquinone that is 2-decaprenyl-1,4-benzoquinone carrying additional methyl and methoxy substituents at positions 3 and 6 respectively.
A dihydroxybenzoic acid that is 3,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogen at position 5 is substituted by a decaprenyl group.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is 4-hydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 5 are substituted by a methoxy and a decaprenyl group.
A drug which increases appetite.
